for however many years HILT

00:02:07.420 --> 00:02:10.039
has been in existence now.

00:02:10.039 --> 00:02:13.500
And talked about that on and
on and over and over again.

00:02:13.500 --> 00:02:16.160
And I think it's a blending of
these two things in some way.

00:02:16.160 --> 00:02:20.450
The art and science, focusing
on the science today.

00:02:20.450 --> 00:02:22.970
So I want to talk
about how we can

00:02:22.970 --> 00:02:26.330
get better and the role
of peer observation

00:02:26.330 --> 00:02:28.320
as part of that process.

00:02:28.320 --> 00:02:31.990
So this is from some
work of Anders Ericsson.

00:02:31.990 --> 00:02:33.730
Some of you may know.

00:02:33.730 --> 00:02:36.900
A psychologist
originally from Sweden

00:02:36.900 --> 00:02:39.020
and had most of his
career in the US.

00:02:39.020 --> 00:02:41.060
And he talked about
looking at something he

00:02:41.060 --> 00:02:42.450
calls "deliberative practice."

00:02:42.450 --> 00:02:44.700
Some people call
it guided mastery.

00:02:44.700 --> 00:02:46.370
And this notion that
just because you

00:02:46.370 --> 00:02:50.540
do something for a long time
doesn't mean we get better

00:02:50.540 --> 00:02:53.480
at it, that you
need to reflect, you

00:02:53.480 --> 00:02:57.530
need to have other people
helping you to do better.

00:02:57.530 --> 00:02:59.570
And he's done this
work with everything

00:02:59.570 --> 00:03:02.600
from chess players
to radiologists,

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:04.130
looking at the same thing.

00:03:04.130 --> 00:03:06.500
And he talks about this
notion that as we get better,

00:03:06.500 --> 00:03:10.760
we can plateau at a
number of different levels

00:03:10.760 --> 00:03:14.150
depending on whether we
continue to do that reflection

00:03:14.150 --> 00:03:17.670
and get feedback and act on
the feedback and so forth.

00:03:17.670 --> 00:03:22.750
And even though these everyday
skills become very automatic

00:03:22.750 --> 00:03:24.380
and we sort of like
that sometimes--

00:03:24.380 --> 00:03:26.060
we don't have to think
about what we do,

00:03:26.060 --> 00:03:28.970
it's just kind of built in,
it's habit, and so forth--

00:03:28.970 --> 00:03:30.620
that doesn't allow
us to continue

00:03:30.620 --> 00:03:32.330
to get better and improve.

00:03:32.330 --> 00:03:34.580
It goes to this arrested
development stage, and then

00:03:34.580 --> 00:03:37.970
ultimately, ideally, up
to expert performance

00:03:37.970 --> 00:03:39.980
if you, in fact, continue
to reflect and get

00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:42.580
feedback and work on it.

00:03:42.580 --> 00:03:44.600
So there's a lot
of stuff going on,

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:46.610
I think, in education
generally right now--

00:03:46.610 --> 00:03:48.590
very much certainly at
the medical school--

00:03:48.590 --> 00:03:51.270
about the role of coaching.

00:03:51.270 --> 00:03:56.030
And we probably know coaching
brings to mind many images.

00:03:56.030 --> 00:03:59.030
There are a lot of personal
coaches that help individuals

00:03:59.030 --> 00:04:01.640
in terms of work-life
balance and figuring out

00:04:01.640 --> 00:04:03.994
how to navigate their careers
and those kinds of things.

00:04:03.994 --> 00:04:05.660
And of course, most
of us had experience

00:04:05.660 --> 00:04:09.020
with athletic coaches at
some point in our lives.

00:04:09.020 --> 00:04:10.160
And what is a coach?

00:04:10.160 --> 00:04:12.140
It's usually a close,
personal relationship

00:04:12.140 --> 00:04:14.300
with an individual,
and that person

00:04:14.300 --> 00:04:19.700
has the freedom to really
observe you, make comments

00:04:19.700 --> 00:04:21.860
about things that
you could do better.

00:04:21.860 --> 00:04:24.110
And then you work on that,
and you get observed again,

00:04:24.110 --> 00:04:26.930
and that's, again, leading
up to that expert performance

00:04:26.930 --> 00:04:29.990
kind of with that
guided mastery notion.

00:04:29.990 --> 00:04:33.410
And so what we've tried to do
is blend this idea of coaching

00:04:33.410 --> 00:04:37.880
with a peer observation program.

00:04:37.880 --> 00:04:39.710
So this notion is
that teachers like

00:04:39.710 --> 00:04:44.360
you will come and work with
you, watch you, and give you

00:04:44.360 --> 00:04:47.880
feedback on things that
you're doing quite well

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:50.790
and things that maybe you
could do a little bit better.

00:04:50.790 --> 00:04:52.400
And so this is a
list of the sorts

00:04:52.400 --> 00:04:55.640
of things that are built
into this notion of peer

00:04:55.640 --> 00:04:56.410
observation.

00:04:56.410 --> 00:04:58.130
Now it sometimes
feels like you're

00:04:58.130 --> 00:04:59.650
under the magnifying glass.

00:04:59.650 --> 00:05:03.230
And when we first talk about
that with people there's

00:05:03.230 --> 00:05:04.940
a little bit of, I'm
not so sure I really

00:05:04.940 --> 00:05:07.320
want somebody in my
classroom watching what I do.

00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:09.020
What is that going to feel like?

00:05:09.020 --> 00:05:11.600
But the reality is people
can get used to this

00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:15.440
and wind up finding that it's
very helpful, whether it's

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:19.920
about looking at specific
pedagogical approaches.

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:21.960
In fact, practice giving
feedback to each other

00:05:21.960 --> 00:05:23.360
is good because it helps
you to give feedback

00:05:23.360 --> 00:05:25.130
to your learners,
which is a challenge

00:05:25.130 --> 00:05:27.230
for a lot of our faculty.

00:05:27.230 --> 00:05:29.470
Allows us to document
our teaching activities

00:05:29.470 --> 00:05:30.770
better and so forth.

00:05:30.770 --> 00:05:33.330
All these things
that you see here.

00:05:33.330 --> 00:05:34.970
And the reality is
we think everyone

00:05:34.970 --> 00:05:37.830
can learn to become an
effective peer observer.

00:05:37.830 --> 00:05:42.620
Now, doing this often depends
on developing these skills

00:05:42.620 --> 00:05:44.169
in a formal way,
and I'll tell you

00:05:44.169 --> 00:05:45.460
how long we've been doing this.

00:05:45.460 --> 00:05:47.500
This is from a symposium
we ran at our Academy

00:05:47.500 --> 00:05:50.980
at the med school in 2011.

00:05:50.980 --> 00:05:53.039
So we've been talking
about this for a while.

00:05:53.039 --> 00:05:54.580
We've had an interest
group, in fact.

00:05:54.580 --> 00:05:55.704
We've been working on this.

00:05:55.704 --> 00:05:57.950
We've done research
on some of the ways

00:05:57.950 --> 00:06:02.120
of thinking about and doing
peer observation as well.

00:06:02.120 --> 00:06:05.150
And it has taken us seven-- we
implemented it a year ago, so

00:06:05.150 --> 00:06:08.671
six, seven years to really
get the program formally up

00:06:08.671 --> 00:06:09.170
and running.

00:06:09.170 --> 00:06:11.600
So it does take time
to get into this,

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:14.570
but I think it can
be very helpful.

00:06:14.570 --> 00:06:16.370
Our new curriculum
is based on something

00:06:16.370 --> 00:06:19.630
called case-based
collaborative learning.

00:06:19.630 --> 00:06:23.360
And so this new format, which is
a blend of team-based learning,

00:06:23.360 --> 00:06:27.170
case-based learning, a little
bit of problem-based learning

00:06:27.170 --> 00:06:31.610
kind of all rolled into one
fusion for the medical school,

00:06:31.610 --> 00:06:34.070
has specific elements
about how you do it well.

00:06:34.070 --> 00:06:36.360
So we had a group that
got together and said,

00:06:36.360 --> 00:06:40.790
what are the key parts of
teaching in this new format?

00:06:40.790 --> 00:06:43.520
And we've actually published
as well the same kind of thing

00:06:43.520 --> 00:06:46.160
for lecturing a few
years ago that we've also

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:47.840
used for peer observations.

00:06:47.840 --> 00:06:49.960
So starting out
with an instrument--

00:06:49.960 --> 00:06:54.110
and I think we've handed out
one of the papers that has

00:06:54.110 --> 00:06:56.540
an instrument embedded in it.

00:06:56.540 --> 00:06:58.640
Starting out with an
instrument is really helpful

00:06:58.640 --> 00:07:01.300
because that instrument
helps you to think about

00:07:01.300 --> 00:07:04.460
your teaching, just
looking at the instrument,

00:07:04.460 --> 00:07:08.450
and it helps you make more
objective observations

00:07:08.450 --> 00:07:10.230
of what you're looking at.

00:07:10.230 --> 00:07:11.510
So it's very helpful.

00:07:11.510 --> 00:07:13.700
When we started talking
about peer observation,

00:07:13.700 --> 00:07:16.400
doing this with our
faculty, it was actually

00:07:16.400 --> 00:07:19.160
quite well received.

00:07:19.160 --> 00:07:24.110
In terms of using this
worksheet, most people, 73%,

00:07:24.110 --> 00:07:26.320
thought it was extremely
helpful or helpful

00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:30.050
in identifying and discussing
new teaching techniques.

00:07:30.050 --> 00:07:33.080
So again, even after we had
done faculty development

00:07:33.080 --> 00:07:35.270
for this process,
the peer observation

00:07:35.270 --> 00:07:37.670
enhanced the faculty
development that we

00:07:37.670 --> 00:07:39.890
did for teaching
in this new format.

00:07:39.890 --> 00:07:43.440
And 90% found-- you can
see-- that the observation

00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:46.950
debriefing was either
helpful or extremely helpful.

00:07:46.950 --> 00:07:48.470
So this notion,
again, that I'm now

00:07:48.470 --> 00:07:51.320
getting feedback that's
actionable, that's

00:07:51.320 --> 00:07:53.720
tied to these specific
elements that we think

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:56.540
are important for the
teaching, turned out

00:07:56.540 --> 00:07:59.830
to be very productive.

00:07:59.830 --> 00:08:03.350
In terms of setting this up
there are different models.

00:08:03.350 --> 00:08:06.040
This peer review
model, which is kind

00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:09.110
of what the observation I've
been describing is about.

00:08:09.110 --> 00:08:11.500
It's a discussion about
teaching mutual reflection.

00:08:11.500 --> 00:08:14.340
And frankly, having been the
observed and the observer,

00:08:14.340 --> 00:08:17.050
you learn a lot often
by being the observer.

00:08:17.050 --> 00:08:18.130
Wow.

00:08:18.130 --> 00:08:20.680
That was a great thing
that that person just did.

00:08:20.680 --> 00:08:23.050
I'll incorporate that
into my teaching as well.

00:08:23.050 --> 00:08:24.940
So it isn't just
the person who's

00:08:24.940 --> 00:08:27.990
providing the initial feedback
who benefits from them.

00:08:27.990 --> 00:08:30.460
And at this point, it's
viewed as purely formative.

00:08:30.460 --> 00:08:33.830
This is just about helping
you to become better.

00:08:33.830 --> 00:08:37.059
And this developmental model,
in terms of competencies,

00:08:37.059 --> 00:08:39.130
again, if you have a
more formal instrument

00:08:39.130 --> 00:08:41.267
and talk about the
elements of competence

00:08:41.267 --> 00:08:42.850
that you want your
teacher to develop,

00:08:42.850 --> 00:08:44.480
you can do that as well.

00:08:44.480 --> 00:08:46.960
And then the last one is
the revaluation model.

00:08:46.960 --> 00:08:49.670
This is one we haven't
really implemented yet

00:08:49.670 --> 00:08:51.190
but we are talking about it.

00:08:51.190 --> 00:08:54.070
So as we think about
aligning those incentives,

00:08:54.070 --> 00:08:57.010
how do we potentially
even promote, reward,

00:08:57.010 --> 00:09:00.100
otherwise incentivize
people who make

00:09:00.100 --> 00:09:05.650
education a focal point of
their career in the university?

00:09:05.650 --> 00:09:06.929
This may be a way to do that.

00:09:06.929 --> 00:09:08.470
People say, well,
I'm a good teacher.

00:09:08.470 --> 00:09:09.340
Well, how do I know?

00:09:09.340 --> 00:09:10.756
Maybe you're on a
promotion board,

00:09:10.756 --> 00:09:12.640
or you're a
departmental committee.

00:09:12.640 --> 00:09:14.275
How do I know you're
a good teacher?

00:09:14.275 --> 00:09:16.190
Well, you say, well,
my students like me.

00:09:16.190 --> 00:09:19.180
And that's always been brought
up as a suspicious thing.

00:09:19.180 --> 00:09:21.640
The students, what are they
really evaluating when they

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:23.260
say that you're a good teacher?

00:09:23.260 --> 00:09:25.270
So this is a more objective way.

00:09:25.270 --> 00:09:27.700
We train our
observers sufficiently

00:09:27.700 --> 00:09:30.590
that we feel like there is
inter-rater reliability,

00:09:30.590 --> 00:09:32.560
they're using a
valid instrument,

00:09:32.560 --> 00:09:35.620
that we could potentially
use this down the road

00:09:35.620 --> 00:09:38.680
to help people get rewarded
for their teaching.

00:09:38.680 --> 00:09:41.350
And we're not at that
level yet, but we're

00:09:41.350 --> 00:09:46.510
building, potentially, up to
that implementation for them.

00:09:46.510 --> 00:09:48.340
So quickly, I'll just summarize.

00:09:48.340 --> 00:09:51.000
We all can be
better as teachers.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:53.620
I think whatever level you're
at, we all can have better.

00:09:53.620 --> 00:09:55.420
But without this
deliberative practice

00:09:55.420 --> 00:09:58.870
we're likely, in fact, not just
a plateau, but to get worse.

00:09:58.870 --> 00:10:01.930
One of the famous
sayings in K12 education

00:10:01.930 --> 00:10:03.890
is, have you taught
for 30 years or did

00:10:03.890 --> 00:10:06.310
you teach one year 30 times?

00:10:06.310 --> 00:10:08.860
Have you made any
changes to the way

00:10:08.860 --> 00:10:12.610
that you practice, if you will,
in terms of your teaching.

00:10:12.610 --> 00:10:16.480
And peer observation not only is
a way to improve your teaching,

00:10:16.480 --> 00:10:18.930
but frankly the interactions
with your colleagues

00:10:18.930 --> 00:10:21.950
is a very rewarding thing
to engage in as well.

00:10:21.950 --> 00:10:25.270
And again, can be used for
either formative or summative

00:10:25.270 --> 00:10:26.360
assessment.

00:10:26.360 --> 00:10:26.860
All right.

00:10:26.860 --> 00:10:30.220
So again, just a brief
overview of part of what

00:10:30.220 --> 00:10:32.020
we hope to deal with today.

