00:12:02.390 --> 00:12:05.030
For our first year--

00:12:05.030 --> 00:12:07.194
We have six classroom
courses in the first year.

00:12:07.194 --> 00:12:09.110
And so every student has
to take every course.

00:12:09.110 --> 00:12:10.850
So the entire class is being--

00:12:10.850 --> 00:12:11.530
Core faculty.

00:12:11.530 --> 00:12:12.650
--in each of the courses.

00:12:12.650 --> 00:12:16.950
So it's probably about 40% of--

00:12:16.950 --> 00:12:18.060
Of that first year--

00:12:18.060 --> 00:12:19.271
Of the first year faculty.

00:12:19.271 --> 00:12:21.020
Because you have that
ability to focus in.

00:12:21.020 --> 00:12:21.740
Yeah.

00:12:21.740 --> 00:12:21.920
Yeah.

00:12:21.920 --> 00:12:22.420
Right.

00:12:22.420 --> 00:12:23.170
OK.

00:12:23.170 --> 00:12:25.720
And it's all been
completely voluntary.

00:12:25.720 --> 00:12:28.980
I mean, people are
signing up for it.

00:12:28.980 --> 00:12:32.640
And it's-- well, no, no,
it is totally voluntary.

00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:34.320
And that's been one
of the challenges,

00:12:34.320 --> 00:12:37.210
is to get people to
understand that it really just

00:12:37.210 --> 00:12:40.027
is coaching and not evaluative.

00:12:42.770 --> 00:12:43.280
OK.

00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:46.410
So Julia, will you
take it from here?

00:12:46.410 --> 00:12:47.095
Hello.

00:12:47.095 --> 00:12:49.400
Can you hear me?

00:12:49.400 --> 00:12:52.310
So I'm going to pan out
a bit and talk about--

00:12:52.310 --> 00:12:57.650
give you a brief overview on
the motivation, design process,

00:12:57.650 --> 00:13:00.350
its usage cases in
the recent publication

00:13:00.350 --> 00:13:04.250
of Career Framework for
Advancing University Teaching.

00:13:04.250 --> 00:13:07.010
I was actually part
of this working group.

00:13:07.010 --> 00:13:12.290
The publication is a culmination
of a 3 and 1/2 year global

00:13:12.290 --> 00:13:17.840
effort to develop a open
access tool for people

00:13:17.840 --> 00:13:22.520
to assess, evaluate, reward
teaching achievement.

00:13:22.520 --> 00:13:24.590
And really, I want
to use this platform

00:13:24.590 --> 00:13:27.800
as well to hopefully spark
some conversation about

00:13:27.800 --> 00:13:30.650
whether or not this is
actually relevant for Harvard

00:13:30.650 --> 00:13:33.660
or different cohorts at Harvard
who we're actually depending on

00:13:33.660 --> 00:13:35.640
for teaching.

00:13:35.640 --> 00:13:38.780
So this slide is
meant to hopefully

00:13:38.780 --> 00:13:42.410
impress upon you the rigor with
which this study was actually

00:13:42.410 --> 00:13:42.910
done.

00:13:42.910 --> 00:13:44.910
So it's led by Dr.
Ruth Graham, who

00:13:44.910 --> 00:13:47.000
is actually a
professor at Imperial

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.540
College in mechanical
engineering and has

00:13:49.540 --> 00:13:51.170
since becoming a consultant.

00:13:51.170 --> 00:13:54.960
But the initial draft
of the framework

00:13:54.960 --> 00:14:00.260
was informed by pedagogy
literature and education

00:14:00.260 --> 00:14:00.770
literature.

00:14:00.770 --> 00:14:02.353
And then it was sent
out with feedback

00:14:02.353 --> 00:14:05.896
from experts to
university leadership

00:14:05.896 --> 00:14:07.770
across multiple institutions
and disciplines.

00:14:07.770 --> 00:14:09.950
And I wrote
"including medicine,"

00:14:09.950 --> 00:14:13.160
because even though it's a
Royal Academy of Engineering

00:14:13.160 --> 00:14:16.900
publication, it's really meant
to be broadly applicable.

00:14:16.900 --> 00:14:19.880
And what I think
is more powerful

00:14:19.880 --> 00:14:22.190
is the fact that it was
piloted across about

00:14:22.190 --> 00:14:24.470
five different continents,
and all the schools

00:14:24.470 --> 00:14:25.812
are actually listed here.

00:14:25.812 --> 00:14:27.520
So the schools that
are actually listed--

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:29.360
institutions are
listed in parentheses

00:14:29.360 --> 00:14:33.170
are the ones that gave feedback
as opposed to direct piloting.

00:14:33.170 --> 00:14:36.140
But nevertheless,
these were who were

00:14:36.140 --> 00:14:42.140
involved in providing the final
product that was published.

00:14:42.140 --> 00:14:44.050
I was involved in two ways.

00:14:44.050 --> 00:14:45.800
Since I was already
on the committee,

00:14:45.800 --> 00:14:51.180
I had gotten the blessing, as
it were, from our then FAS dean

00:14:51.180 --> 00:14:54.380
Mike Smith, and then also
the SEAS Dean Robert Doyle

00:14:54.380 --> 00:14:57.260
to actually really think
about this framework

00:14:57.260 --> 00:15:00.660
and give feedback in the context
of how I was thinking about it.

00:15:00.660 --> 00:15:02.780
And in particular, in
the context of how do

00:15:02.780 --> 00:15:07.190
we support non-ladder
faculty careers

00:15:07.190 --> 00:15:11.270
who we're actually depending on
more and more for the teaching.

00:15:11.270 --> 00:15:15.240
And then also directly for a
university in South America,

00:15:15.240 --> 00:15:17.000
whereas part of the
senior leadership

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.160
and as part of that
effort we were really

00:15:19.160 --> 00:15:23.420
redefining the structure
of the university.

00:15:23.420 --> 00:15:26.600
And we used this
framework, in fact,

00:15:26.600 --> 00:15:32.450
to inform on a dual promotion
track for the faculty

00:15:32.450 --> 00:15:34.490
there for teaching
and research-based

00:15:34.490 --> 00:15:36.300
or some combination of both.

00:15:36.300 --> 00:15:38.660
So that's the context.

00:15:38.660 --> 00:15:40.850
And certainly there was
a lot of emerging trends

00:15:40.850 --> 00:15:42.680
for the motivation
for developing

00:15:42.680 --> 00:15:49.550
this framework, certainly in
Europe and Asia and elsewhere.

00:15:49.550 --> 00:15:53.540
As fees were actually
increasing for universities

00:15:53.540 --> 00:15:56.550
whereas they used to be free,
there was more and more demands

00:15:56.550 --> 00:15:59.870
now because they have to
pay for better teaching.

00:15:59.870 --> 00:16:03.270
And then I think there was
some discussion about this

00:16:03.270 --> 00:16:06.740
this morning that there's also
competition of online learning

00:16:06.740 --> 00:16:08.460
resources as well.

00:16:08.460 --> 00:16:13.740
Interestingly, also in
Europe and also Asia,

00:16:13.740 --> 00:16:17.480
the governments are actually
linking studentships and fee

00:16:17.480 --> 00:16:19.640
structures to
quality of teaching.

00:16:19.640 --> 00:16:21.920
So there is actually
some linkage

00:16:21.920 --> 00:16:25.130
to that that is actually
encouraging people

00:16:25.130 --> 00:16:27.430
to make the change.

00:16:27.430 --> 00:16:28.460
Encouraging strongly.

00:16:28.460 --> 00:16:31.730
And certainly, I think,
last but not least,

00:16:31.730 --> 00:16:34.310
is that there was recognition
amongst the working

00:16:34.310 --> 00:16:38.090
group and external to it,
that even though there

00:16:38.090 --> 00:16:41.030
is this increased rhetoric,
for lack of a better word,

00:16:41.030 --> 00:16:43.430
for better teaching
amongst the faculty,

00:16:43.430 --> 00:16:46.180
there is really little incentive
for really improving it

00:16:46.180 --> 00:16:48.950
because as long as
you actually pass

00:16:48.950 --> 00:16:52.680
some kind of baseline
teaching quality,

00:16:52.680 --> 00:16:56.480
then beyond that your
promotion chances are really

00:16:56.480 --> 00:16:59.170
tied to research output.

00:16:59.170 --> 00:17:01.220
And what this framework
was trying to do

00:17:01.220 --> 00:17:05.660
was to try to provide a useful
metric for evaluating teaching

00:17:05.660 --> 00:17:09.520
achievement that overcomes
traditional barriers in terms

00:17:09.520 --> 00:17:13.480
of not having necessarily
well-defined things

00:17:13.480 --> 00:17:15.650
for these different levels.

00:17:15.650 --> 00:17:17.800
And what is
particularly interesting

00:17:17.800 --> 00:17:21.460
is that it ties the
successive levels of promotion

00:17:21.460 --> 00:17:25.480
if you will to your
sphere of impact.

00:17:25.480 --> 00:17:30.250
And then what the framework also
provides examples of evidence

00:17:30.250 --> 00:17:32.750
for what those might look like.

00:17:32.750 --> 00:17:35.840
So just briefly to show those.

00:17:35.840 --> 00:17:39.850
One can imagine that at the
most basic baseline level

00:17:39.850 --> 00:17:43.094
you're an effective teacher
and your sphere of impact

00:17:43.094 --> 00:17:44.260
is going to be the students.

00:17:44.260 --> 00:17:45.926
You're actually
thinking conscientiously

00:17:45.926 --> 00:17:49.540
about how do students learn
and how to effectively teach.

00:17:49.540 --> 00:17:51.360
If you wanted to go
up to the next level,

00:17:51.360 --> 00:17:53.260
then that sphere
of impact actually

00:17:53.260 --> 00:17:58.090
has to extend to maybe
relevance to the broader

00:17:58.090 --> 00:18:00.520
institutional context or
that you're actually giving

00:18:00.520 --> 00:18:03.470
mentorship to your colleagues.

00:18:03.470 --> 00:18:05.880
With a third track,
as we're moving up,

00:18:05.880 --> 00:18:07.630
we decided that we're
going to split those

00:18:07.630 --> 00:18:08.990
into two different ways.

00:18:08.990 --> 00:18:12.580
One is if you
continue to improve

00:18:12.580 --> 00:18:15.610
the practice of teaching
and the sphere of impact

00:18:15.610 --> 00:18:19.690
to extend to a larger cohort
and beyond the university,

00:18:19.690 --> 00:18:21.310
but it also allows
for people who

00:18:21.310 --> 00:18:24.580
want to do scholarly research
to also advance in this way

00:18:24.580 --> 00:18:27.470
if they're doing
research on pedagogy

00:18:27.470 --> 00:18:30.520
and other similar things.

00:18:30.520 --> 00:18:32.340
And then, of course--

00:18:32.340 --> 00:18:34.630
and then, of course,
the highest level.

00:18:34.630 --> 00:18:37.550
And so obviously you're
not meant to read all this.

00:18:37.550 --> 00:18:40.210
For anybody interested, I've
got the actual publication

00:18:40.210 --> 00:18:42.280
that goes into the details.

00:18:42.280 --> 00:18:44.350
But really, it's broadly--

00:18:44.350 --> 00:18:46.450
one of the key things
was giving examples

00:18:46.450 --> 00:18:48.700
based on all these piloted
schools of what that might

00:18:48.700 --> 00:18:50.170
mean for the different levels.

00:18:50.170 --> 00:18:54.490
And these levels can be
broadly separated into two

00:18:54.490 --> 00:18:56.660
major categories.

00:18:56.660 --> 00:19:00.430
One is the approach, which is
really due to the instructor

00:19:00.430 --> 00:19:01.000
himself.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:05.440
Some self-introspection about
your teaching as well as

00:19:05.440 --> 00:19:08.350
your professional activities.

00:19:08.350 --> 00:19:11.620
The impact part,
which is assessed

00:19:11.620 --> 00:19:14.890
through both direct and indirect
measures of student learning,

00:19:14.890 --> 00:19:19.520
as well as kind of what your
peers think about your teaching

00:19:19.520 --> 00:19:22.960
to, for example, Rich's point.

00:19:22.960 --> 00:19:24.142
And so just an example.

00:19:24.142 --> 00:19:26.350
There was a number of
universities that have actually

00:19:26.350 --> 00:19:28.210
used this framework
in different ways

00:19:28.210 --> 00:19:31.030
to kind of put it into the
context of how it might work

00:19:31.030 --> 00:19:33.070
in a particular
university, whether it's

00:19:33.070 --> 00:19:35.640
to slice through this
in different ways,

00:19:35.640 --> 00:19:40.090
or whether as a
metric for where you

00:19:40.090 --> 00:19:44.260
want to be in terms of
assessing the different people.

00:19:44.260 --> 00:19:46.260
So here, for example,
this is University

00:19:46.260 --> 00:19:49.410
of Twente in the Netherlands.

00:19:49.410 --> 00:19:51.410
This one shows that--

00:19:51.410 --> 00:19:53.170
so for somebody
who chooses to have

00:19:53.170 --> 00:19:56.170
most of their career
in an education track

00:19:56.170 --> 00:19:59.390
there is a baseline
requirement for research.

00:19:59.390 --> 00:20:01.630
But at the same time,
most of the promotion

00:20:01.630 --> 00:20:04.750
is really going to be
tracked to their teaching.

00:20:04.750 --> 00:20:06.670
And what's very
useful and interesting

00:20:06.670 --> 00:20:11.970
about this framework is that, in
fact, this institution is also

00:20:11.970 --> 00:20:14.500
tied to support structure
for helping these people

00:20:14.500 --> 00:20:18.290
move up to the different
levels as well.

00:20:18.290 --> 00:20:20.470
And certainly, I list
this as the Netherlands,

00:20:20.470 --> 00:20:23.020
but in fact, the University
College London one looked also

00:20:23.020 --> 00:20:23.860
very much like this.

00:20:23.860 --> 00:20:25.776
So there's a lot of
universities that actually

00:20:25.776 --> 00:20:28.000
use this framework to
kind of make changes

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:30.802
to their institutions.

00:20:30.802 --> 00:20:33.260
And as I said, the governments
have really gotten involved.

00:20:33.260 --> 00:20:36.280
So for example,
in Malaysia, there

00:20:36.280 --> 00:20:38.290
was a national government
call that universities

00:20:38.290 --> 00:20:42.160
had to develop some kind of
unified academic pathway.

00:20:42.160 --> 00:20:44.320
And so a number of
universities have

00:20:44.320 --> 00:20:49.000
been using this framework to try
to work that out collectively.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:51.160
What's really amazing
is that, as a whole,

00:20:51.160 --> 00:20:54.366
the Dutch government
and most of the Dutch--

00:20:54.366 --> 00:20:55.990
some large factions
at the universities

00:20:55.990 --> 00:20:59.410
have really kind of
embraced this to the extent

00:20:59.410 --> 00:21:04.120
that the minister of
education, who actually was

00:21:04.120 --> 00:21:07.300
on this committee before he
became minister of education,

00:21:07.300 --> 00:21:12.430
has decided to actually put
money towards this grant

00:21:12.430 --> 00:21:14.480
to say, we want better
teaching so I'm going

00:21:14.480 --> 00:21:17.230
to invest in better teaching.

00:21:17.230 --> 00:21:20.560
And so they've actually
mapped these different levels

00:21:20.560 --> 00:21:23.470
that people can
apply for and get

00:21:23.470 --> 00:21:25.720
recognized for to
these different tracks

00:21:25.720 --> 00:21:27.550
of this framework.

00:21:27.550 --> 00:21:33.220
And in the initial
run of this in 2017

00:21:33.220 --> 00:21:36.130
I noticed that they actually
invested 6 million euros

00:21:36.130 --> 00:21:36.670
into this.

00:21:36.670 --> 00:21:39.830
And these were the number of
fellows at the different levels

00:21:39.830 --> 00:21:41.830
that are being supported
now to actually improve

00:21:41.830 --> 00:21:44.320
their teaching.

00:21:44.320 --> 00:21:50.982
And so this was published
formally in April 2018.

00:21:50.982 --> 00:21:54.080
Some 30-plus universities
that we know of actually

00:21:54.080 --> 00:21:56.470
use this to inform or
enact changes in some way

00:21:56.470 --> 00:21:57.290
in universities.

00:21:57.290 --> 00:22:00.390
So there is this global trend
towards really recognizing

00:22:00.390 --> 00:22:02.150
teaching more.

00:22:02.150 --> 00:22:05.400
And then I want to kind of
bring us back to Harvard

00:22:05.400 --> 00:22:10.110
with that particular context,
is can we use this framework

00:22:10.110 --> 00:22:13.440
to incentivize
our ladder faculty

00:22:13.440 --> 00:22:16.440
to be better teachers in
some ways and to support?

00:22:16.440 --> 00:22:19.800
But more importantly, something
that I've been thinking about

00:22:19.800 --> 00:22:24.150
is, can we actually better
support the non-ladder faculty

00:22:24.150 --> 00:22:26.790
who we're actually
depending more and more

00:22:26.790 --> 00:22:28.704
on for our teaching purposes.

00:22:28.704 --> 00:22:30.370
So if we actually
look at these numbers,

00:22:30.370 --> 00:22:33.000
they make up a pretty large
fraction of the faculty

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:36.250
that we're depending on.

00:22:36.250 --> 00:22:38.790
And so if I were just--

00:22:38.790 --> 00:22:41.310
this is obviously not
correct, but if I were just

00:22:41.310 --> 00:22:46.860
to attempt to map that to
this particular framework,

00:22:46.860 --> 00:22:49.800
this might be the level of where
we would actually place them.

00:22:49.800 --> 00:22:52.680
But as I was interviewing
different people

00:22:52.680 --> 00:22:54.180
in different
departments, I realized

00:22:54.180 --> 00:22:59.070
that the expectations of
these different people

00:22:59.070 --> 00:23:02.210
are very different based on
what departments they are at.

00:23:02.210 --> 00:23:04.930
So I just wanted to
put that out there.

00:23:04.930 --> 00:23:08.610
So really my question to you
is, is a modified framework

00:23:08.610 --> 00:23:09.690
relevant for Harvard?

00:23:09.690 --> 00:23:15.240
Is it useful to support
non-ladder careers,

00:23:15.240 --> 00:23:20.910
or as a means to reward
teaching for ladder faculty?

00:23:20.910 --> 00:23:25.720
And then how do we actually
support and incentivize?

00:23:25.720 --> 00:23:27.747
And then, of course, the
goals today is really--

00:23:27.747 --> 00:23:29.580
I think we want to ask
the question of this,

00:23:29.580 --> 00:23:32.820
how do we support all faculty
to be better teachers here?

00:23:32.820 --> 00:23:35.070
We're going to break out
into groups and discuss this.

00:23:35.070 --> 00:23:37.530
And then, also, how
do we incentivize

00:23:37.530 --> 00:23:39.120
this improvement in teaching?

00:23:39.120 --> 00:23:45.500
And I'll just leave that up
about next steps in this study.

00:23:45.500 --> 00:23:49.170
But I'll just leave it up
during the question session.

00:23:52.040 --> 00:23:56.956
Clarifying questions for
Julia about the framework?

00:23:56.956 --> 00:23:59.820
I just have one question.

00:23:59.820 --> 00:24:01.320
Did you put any--

00:24:01.320 --> 00:24:06.780
did the committee try to
look at dollars at all?

00:24:06.780 --> 00:24:09.960
And you hear all the time,
well, research faculty

00:24:09.960 --> 00:24:12.600
bring in overhead from grants.

00:24:12.600 --> 00:24:15.790
Teaching faculty, if you
have these teaching faculty,

00:24:15.790 --> 00:24:17.430
they don't bring in dollars.

00:24:17.430 --> 00:24:20.970
Of course, they might
bring in tuition.

00:24:20.970 --> 00:24:23.540
So I wonder if you
looked at money at all?

00:24:23.540 --> 00:24:28.170
Not as a direct consequence
of what we wrote.

00:24:28.170 --> 00:24:31.770
But I think money was
talked about indirectly

00:24:31.770 --> 00:24:33.660
in that a lot of
universities actually

00:24:33.660 --> 00:24:36.520
do depend on student fees.

00:24:36.520 --> 00:24:38.250
So in that case,
this is where I was

00:24:38.250 --> 00:24:40.290
saying that as student
fees are going up,

00:24:40.290 --> 00:24:44.530
there was a demand
for better teaching.

00:24:44.530 --> 00:24:47.670
And so I think really in
that particular sense.

00:24:47.670 --> 00:24:49.905
But I think it was
more than we recognized

00:24:49.905 --> 00:24:52.230
that better teaching
was a need and there

00:24:52.230 --> 00:24:53.640
was no support for it.

00:24:53.640 --> 00:24:55.860
What a lot of the
universities have done

00:24:55.860 --> 00:24:59.450
is actually invested their own
dollars in supporting this.

00:24:59.450 --> 00:25:02.370
So the university said,
this is an important thing,

00:25:02.370 --> 00:25:04.070
we're going to invest in it.

00:25:04.070 --> 00:25:05.540
The problem is that
oftentimes it's

00:25:05.540 --> 00:25:06.960
where this is an
important thing,

00:25:06.960 --> 00:25:09.650
just do it along with
everything else and whatever.

00:25:09.650 --> 00:25:12.390
So I think that was
something that we

00:25:12.390 --> 00:25:14.130
were really conscientious of.

00:25:14.130 --> 00:25:17.910
And a lot of universities who
did this really did invest.

00:25:17.910 --> 00:25:20.430
So I just have a
question, and this is only

00:25:20.430 --> 00:25:23.500
based on having taught
in Europe for a while

00:25:23.500 --> 00:25:26.230
as well as having worked here.

00:25:26.230 --> 00:25:29.010
I'm wondering if you've seen
any differentials in terms

00:25:29.010 --> 00:25:33.455
of national culture with regards
to how quickly universities

00:25:33.455 --> 00:25:35.630
and teachers are
picking this up?

00:25:35.630 --> 00:25:37.970
For example, the
Netherlands for a long time

00:25:37.970 --> 00:25:39.810
was way ahead of
the rest of Europe

00:25:39.810 --> 00:25:42.240
in terms of emphasis
on teaching,

00:25:42.240 --> 00:25:45.670
emphasis on experiential
learning, active learning.

00:25:45.670 --> 00:25:48.320
And because they're
national systems as well--

00:25:48.320 --> 00:25:51.720
they're primarily public system
versus the US' privatized

00:25:51.720 --> 00:25:52.560
system--

00:25:52.560 --> 00:25:54.210
have you seen any
differences in terms

00:25:54.210 --> 00:25:58.130
of how large institutions,
like governments in Netherlands

00:25:58.130 --> 00:26:02.220
or the EU versus other systems
like the US, are supporting it,

00:26:02.220 --> 00:26:04.380
and how is that
affecting adoption rate?

00:26:04.380 --> 00:26:07.320
So I think with the Netherlands,
I mean, it's really amazing,

00:26:07.320 --> 00:26:08.900
because they decided
to take this--

00:26:08.900 --> 00:26:12.264
I mean, to begin
with, all faculty

00:26:12.264 --> 00:26:13.680
at universities
in the Netherlands

00:26:13.680 --> 00:26:15.960
actually have to have some
kind of teaching certification.

00:26:15.960 --> 00:26:18.001
So they already have to
go through that training.

00:26:18.001 --> 00:26:22.500
So it wasn't that much
of a jump to enact.

00:26:22.500 --> 00:26:26.580
But in terms of other
institutions-- so for example,

00:26:26.580 --> 00:26:29.002
Cambridge, Oxford,
I was just there,

00:26:29.002 --> 00:26:30.210
they were kind of resistance.

00:26:30.210 --> 00:26:33.420
They're kind of like us.

00:26:33.420 --> 00:26:37.710
